\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {1}{\ignorespaces \textbf  {Timing Cell and S-Functional Floor: operational truth is a cell $C \subseteq \Delta P$-space with positive measure, and the S-functional satisfies $S(R,x;\,C) \geq \beta > 0$ for all $x$.} (\textbf  {A}) Histogram of 4000 simulated $\Delta P$ values (blue bars, density-normalised) with the timing cell $C$ bounded by red dashed lines. The finite-width interval captures a substantial fraction of the distribution; no point predicate ($\Delta P = c$) could do so with positive measure. (\textbf  {B}) S-functional $S(R,x;\,C)$ versus position $x$ for a one-dimensional cell $C = [0.3,\,0.7]$ (blue curve). Outside $C$ the function is the V-shaped distance to the nearest cell boundary; inside $C$ it is flat at the floor $\beta $ (red dashed line, green shading), confirming that $\inf _{x} S = \beta > 0$ strictly. (\textbf  {C}) Three-dimensional S-functional surface over a two-dimensional $\Delta P$ domain, where the cell is the square $[0.3,0.7]^2$. The surface is a four-sided bowl whose flat base lies at $\beta $; the gradient outside the cell encodes the distance to the nearest cell face. (\textbf  {D}) Effective measure $\tau (C) + \beta $ versus cell width for four values of the floor parameter $\beta $ ($0.02$, $0.05$, $0.10$, $0.20$). All curves are strictly positive for all cell widths, demonstrating that the floor $\beta $ provides a hard lower bound independent of cell geometry.}}{4}{figure.caption.1}\protected@file@percent }
\providecommand*\caption@xref[2]{\@setref\relax\@undefined{#1}}
\newlabel{fig:cell_floor}{{1}{4}{\textbf {Timing Cell and S-Functional Floor: operational truth is a cell $C \subseteq \Delta P$-space with positive measure, and the S-functional satisfies $S(R,x;\,C) \geq \beta > 0$ for all $x$.} (\textbf {A}) Histogram of 4000 simulated $\Delta P$ values (blue bars, density-normalised) with the timing cell $C$ bounded by red dashed lines. The finite-width interval captures a substantial fraction of the distribution; no point predicate ($\Delta P = c$) could do so with positive measure. (\textbf {B}) S-functional $S(R,x;\,C)$ versus position $x$ for a one-dimensional cell $C = [0.3,\,0.7]$ (blue curve). Outside $C$ the function is the V-shaped distance to the nearest cell boundary; inside $C$ it is flat at the floor $\beta $ (red dashed line, green shading), confirming that $\inf _{x} S = \beta > 0$ strictly. (\textbf {C}) Three-dimensional S-functional surface over a two-dimensional $\Delta P$ domain, where the cell is the square $[0.3,0.7]^2$. The surface is a four-sided bowl whose flat base lies at $\beta $; the gradient outside the cell encodes the distance to the nearest cell face. (\textbf {D}) Effective measure $\tau (C) + \beta $ versus cell width for four values of the floor parameter $\beta $ ($0.02$, $0.05$, $0.10$, $0.20$). All curves are strictly positive for all cell widths, demonstrating that the floor $\beta $ provides a hard lower bound independent of cell geometry}{figure.caption.1}{}}
