\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3}{\ignorespaces \textbf  {COMPILE/EXECUTE Phase Separation Forced by the Receiver Uncertainty Principle $\sigma _K \cdot \sigma _Y \geq \hbar _R = \beta \tau $: trajectory accumulation and action firing are mutually exclusive phases.} (\textbf  {A}) Antiphase oscillation of $\sigma _K$ (knowledge uncertainty, blue), $\sigma _Y$ (action uncertainty, red), and their product $\sigma _K \cdot \sigma _Y$ (green dotted) over four complete cycles. The product never drops below the floor $\hbar _R$ (grey dashed), and $\sigma _K$ is maximised precisely when $\sigma _Y$ is minimised, and vice versa. (\textbf  {B}) Timeline of alternating COMPILE (blue) and EXECUTE (red) blocks over ten cycles. Block durations are drawn from realistic distributions; the two phases tile the time axis without overlap, illustrating the hard mutual exclusion enforced by the uncertainty principle. (\textbf  {C}) Three-dimensional action-rate surface over $(\sigma _K,\,\sigma _Y) \in [0,1]^2$. The surface is nonzero only in the region $\sigma _K < 0.2$ (deep EXECUTE phase) and grows with $\sigma _Y$, reflecting that actions fire at high confidence only after the trajectory has been fully resolved. (\textbf  {D}) Action counts per block for 120 alternating blocks. COMPILE blocks (blue) fire zero actions by construction; EXECUTE blocks (red) fire a Poisson-distributed count $\sim \mathrm  {Poi}(3.5)$, confirming that no action escapes the phase boundary.}}{7}{figure.caption.3}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:phase_separation}{{3}{7}{\textbf {COMPILE/EXECUTE Phase Separation Forced by the Receiver Uncertainty Principle $\sigma _K \cdot \sigma _Y \geq \hbar _R = \beta \tau $: trajectory accumulation and action firing are mutually exclusive phases.} (\textbf {A}) Antiphase oscillation of $\sigma _K$ (knowledge uncertainty, blue), $\sigma _Y$ (action uncertainty, red), and their product $\sigma _K \cdot \sigma _Y$ (green dotted) over four complete cycles. The product never drops below the floor $\hbar _R$ (grey dashed), and $\sigma _K$ is maximised precisely when $\sigma _Y$ is minimised, and vice versa. (\textbf {B}) Timeline of alternating COMPILE (blue) and EXECUTE (red) blocks over ten cycles. Block durations are drawn from realistic distributions; the two phases tile the time axis without overlap, illustrating the hard mutual exclusion enforced by the uncertainty principle. (\textbf {C}) Three-dimensional action-rate surface over $(\sigma _K,\,\sigma _Y) \in [0,1]^2$. The surface is nonzero only in the region $\sigma _K < 0.2$ (deep EXECUTE phase) and grows with $\sigma _Y$, reflecting that actions fire at high confidence only after the trajectory has been fully resolved. (\textbf {D}) Action counts per block for 120 alternating blocks. COMPILE blocks (blue) fire zero actions by construction; EXECUTE blocks (red) fire a Poisson-distributed count $\sim \mathrm {Poi}(3.5)$, confirming that no action escapes the phase boundary}{figure.caption.3}{}}
